'Eh?'\par
'If you recall, sir, owing to the temporary indisposition of the vicar, Mr. Pinker will be in sole charge of the school treat tomorrow, and he views the prospect with not unnatural qualms. There is a somewhat lawless element among the school children of Totleigh-in-the-Wold, and he fears the worst.'\par
'Well, tell Stiffy to take a couple of minutes off from the pep talk and listen to your communique.'\par
'Very good, sir.'\par
He was absent quite a time - so long, in fact, that I was dressed when he returned.\par
'I saw Miss Byng, sir.'\par
'And - ?'\par
'She is still insistent that you restore the statuette to Mr. Plank.'\par
'She's cuckoo. I can't get into the collection room.'\par
'No, sir, but Miss Byng can. She informs me that not long ago Sir Watkyn chanced to drop his key, and she picked it up and omitted to apprise him. Sir Watkyn had another key made, but the original remains in Miss Byng's possession.'\par
I clutched the brow.\par
'You mean she can get into the room any time she feels like it?'\par
'Precisely, sir. Indeed, she has just done so.'\par
And so saying he fished the eyesore from an inner pocket and handed it to me.\par
'Miss Byng suggests that you take the object to Mr. Plank after luncheon. In her droll way she said the meal - I quote her words -would put the necessary stuffing into you and nerve you for the . . . It is somewhat early, sir, but shall I get you a little brandy?'\par
