I was conscious of a thrill of thankfulness for Jeeves's prescience, if prescience is the word I want. I mean that uncanny knack he has of peering into the future and forming his plans and schemes well ahead of time. But for his thoughtful diagnosis of the perils that lay before me, I should at this juncture have been deep in the mulligatawny and no hope of striking for the shore. As it was, I was able to be nonchalant, insouciant and debonair. I was like the fellow I once heard Jeeves speak of who was armed so strong in honesty that somebody's threats passed by him as the idle wind, which he respected not. I think if Spode had been about three feet shorter and not so wide across the shoulders, I would have laughed a mocking laugh and quite possibly have flicked my cambric handkerchief in his face.\par
He was eyeing me piercingly, little knowing what an ass he was going to feel before yonder sun had set. 'I have just searched your room.'\par
'You have? You surprise me. Looking for something, were you?' \par
'You know what I'm looking for. That amber statuette you said your uncle would be so glad to have.'\par
'Oh, that? I understood it was in the collection room.' \par
'Who told you that?' \par
'A usually well-informed source.'\par
'Well, it is no longer in the collection room. Somebody has removed it.'\par
'Most extraordinary.'\par
'And when I say "somebody", I mean a slimy sneak thief of the name of Wooster. The thing isn't in your bedroom, so if it is not in your car, you must have it on you. Turn out your pockets.'\par
I humoured his request, largely influenced by the fact that there was so much of him. A Singer midget would have found me far less obliging. The contents having been placed before him, he snorted in a disappointed way, as if he had hoped for better things, and dived into the car, opening drawers and looking under cushions. And Stiffy, coming along at this moment, drank in his vast trouser seat with a curious eye.\par
'What goes on?' she asked.\par
This time I did laugh that mocking laugh. It seemed to be indicated.\par
'You know that black eyesore thing that was on the dinner table? Apparently it's disappeared, and Spode has got the extraordinary idea that I've pinched it and am holding it... what's the word . . . Not incognito . . . Incommunicado, that's it. He thinks I'm holding it incommunicado.'\par
'He does?'\par
'So he says.'\par
'Man must be an ass.'\par
Spode wheeled around, flushed with his excesses. I was pleased to see that while looking under the seat he had got a bit of oil on his nose. He eyed Stiffy bleakly.\par
'Did you call me an ass?'\par
'Certainly I did. I was taught by a long series of governesses always to speak the truth. The idea of accusing Bertie of taking that statuette.'\par
'It does sound silly,' I agreed. 'Bizarre is perhaps the word.'\par
'The thing's in Uncle Watkyn's collection room.'\par
'It is not in the collection room.'\par
'Who says so?'\par
'I say so.'\par
