It was that soft cough of Jeeves's which always reminds me of a very old sheep clearing its throat on a distant mountain top. He coughed it at me, if you remember, on the occasion when I first swam into his ken wearing the Alpine hat. It generally signifies disapproval, but I've known it to occur also when he's about to touch on a topic of a delicate nature. And when he spoke, I knew that that was what he was going to do now, for there was a sort of hushed note in his voice.\par
'I wonder if I might have a moment of your time, miss?'\par
'Of course, Jeeves.'\par
'It is with reference to Mr. Wooster.'\par
'Oh, yes?'\par
'I must begin by saying that I chanced to be passing the door when Lord Sidcup was speaking to you and inadvertently overheard his lordship's observations on the subject of Mr. Wooster. His lordship has a carrying voice. And I find myself in a somewhat equivocal position, torn between loyalty to my employer and a natural desire to do my duty as a citizen.'\par
'I don't understand you, Jeeves,' said Madeline, which made two of us.\par
He coughed again.\par
'I am anxious not to take a liberty, miss, but if I may speak frankly -'\par
'Please do.'\par
'Thank you, miss. His lordship's words seemed to confirm a rumour which is circulating in the servants' hall that you are contemplating a matrimonial union with Mr. Wooster. Would it be indiscreet of me if I were to inquire if this is so?'\par
'Yes, Jeeves, it is quite true.'\par
'If you will pardon me for saying so, I think you are making a mistake.'\par
